class Solution {
public:
    string smallestSubsequence(string s) {
        int lastOccurrence[26] = {0};
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            lastOccurrence[s[i] - 'a'] = i;
        }
        bool visited[26] = {false};
        string result = "";
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            if (visited[s[i] - 'a']) continue;
            while (!result.empty() && result.back() > s[i] && i < lastOccurrence[result.back() - 'a']) {
                visited[result.back() - 'a'] = false;
                result.pop_back();
            }
            result += s[i];
            visited[s[i] - 'a'] = true;
        }
        return result;
    }
};
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(N)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a greedy strategy to build the lexicographically smallest subsequence by maintaining a stack (implemented as a string) of characters seen so far and ensuring that the top of the stack is always the smallest possible character that can be part of the final result. It keeps track of the last occurrence of each character to decide whether to pop characters from the stack. The visited array ensures that each character is added to the result only once. 
